### File I/O in C#

C# provides comprehensive file I/O capabilities through the `System.IO` namespace.

### File Class (Static Methods)

```csharp
using System.IO;

// Read
string content = File.ReadAllText("file.txt");
string[] lines = File.ReadAllLines("file.txt");
byte[] bytes = File.ReadAllBytes("file.bin");

// Write
File.WriteAllText("file.txt", "Hello World");
File.WriteAllLines("file.txt", new[] { "Line1", "Line2" });
File.WriteAllBytes("file.bin", new byte[] { 0x48, 0x65 });

// Append
File.AppendAllText("file.txt", "More text");
File.AppendAllLines("file.txt", new[] { "More" });
```

### FileInfo Class (Instance Methods)

```csharp
FileInfo file = new FileInfo(@"C:\data\file.txt");

Console.WriteLine($"Name: {file.Name}");
Console.WriteLine($"Size: {file.Length} bytes");
Console.WriteLine($"Extension: {file.Extension}");
Console.WriteLine($"Exists: {file.Exists}");
Console.WriteLine($"Created: {file.CreationTime}");

// Operations
file.CopyTo("copy.txt");
file.MoveTo("new.txt");
file.Delete();
```

### Directory Operations

```csharp
// Create
Directory.CreateDirectory(@"C:\data\subfolder");

// Check existence
bool exists = Directory.Exists(@"C:\data");

// Enumerate
string[] files = Directory.GetFiles(@"C:\data");
string[] dirs = Directory.GetDirectories(@"C:\data");

// Enumerate (lazy, better for large dirs)
foreach (string file in Directory.EnumerateFiles(@"C:\data", "*.txt"))
    Console.WriteLine(file);
```

### Path Operations

```csharp
string dir = Path.GetDirectoryName(path);
string file = Path.GetFileName(path);
string ext = Path.GetExtension(path);
string name = Path.GetFileNameWithoutExtension(path);

string combined = Path.Combine("folder", "sub", "file.txt");
string temp = Path.GetTempFileName();
string tempDir = Path.GetTempPath();
```

### File Access Modes

| Mode | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `FileMode.Create` | Creates new; overwrites if exists |
| `FileMode.Open` | Opens existing; throws if not found |
| `FileMode.OpenOrCreate` | Opens or creates |
| `FileMode.Append` | Opens or creates for appending |

### File Sharing

```csharp
using var fs = new FileStream("file.txt", FileMode.Open,
    FileAccess.Read, FileShare.Read);
```

> **Key Point:** The `File` class provides simple static methods for common operations. Use `FileInfo` when you need multiple operations on the same file. Always use `using` or `try-finally` to ensure file handles are closed. Use `Directory.Enumerate*` for large directories (lazy enumeration).

### Checking File Existence

```csharp
if (File.Exists("file.txt"))
    string content = File.ReadAllText("file.txt");
```

### File Attributes

```csharp
File.SetAttributes("file.txt", FileAttributes.ReadOnly);
FileAttributes attrs = File.GetAttributes("file.txt");
bool isReadOnly = attrs.HasFlag(FileAttributes.ReadOnly);
```

### Temporary Files

```csharp
string tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
File.WriteAllText(tempFile, "Temporary data");
File.Delete(tempFile);
```

codeExample:
using System;
using System.IO;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        string path = "notes.txt";

        // Write
        File.WriteAllText(path, "Hello, C# File I/O!\nThis is a test.");
        Console.WriteLine($"Written to {path}");

        // Read
        if (File.Exists(path))
        {
            string content = File.ReadAllText(path);
            Console.WriteLine($"\nFile content:\n{content}");

            var info = new FileInfo(path);
            Console.WriteLine($"\nSize: {info.Length} bytes");
            Console.WriteLine($"Created: {info.CreationTime}");
        }
    }
}
